<subSubSection id="C30798E0FFE1A132D79146EEAA3CF875" pageId="24" pageNumber="125" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BA2CB6BFFE1A132D79146EEAA3CF875" blockId="24.[151,1436,1934,2031]" pageId="24" pageNumber="125">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFE1A132D79146EEA874F818" bold="true" box="[199,345,1934,1959]" pageId="24" pageNumber="125">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="1326D7EEFFE1A132D63F46EEA883F818" box="[361,430,1934,1959]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1980,2002]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1956]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,1959]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 3. Current records of Stigmella species feeding on plants from the genus Baccharis L." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261788/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="125">
Fig. 
<number id="3DD5D94CFFE1A132D6C846EFA883F818" box="[414,430,1935,1959]" pageId="24" pageNumber="125" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). This species occurs high in the equatorial Andes (
<collectingCountry id="F30A8BFBFFE1A132D4AF46EEAD71F818" box="[1017,1116,1934,1959]" name="Ecuador" pageId="24" pageNumber="125">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
: Napo Province) at altitudes between 
<quantity id="4CE5668EFFE1A132D7AD46D2A8B5F875" box="[251,408,1970,1994]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.75" metricValueMax="3.8" metricValueMin="3.7" pageId="24" pageNumber="125" unit="m" value="3750.0" valueMax="3800.0" valueMin="3700.0">3700–3800 m</quantity>
, in páramo habitats (
<figureCitation id="1326D7EEFFE1A132D5D446D2AA29F875" box="[642,772,1970,1995]" captionStart="FIGURES 97 – 103" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1811,1834]" captionTargetBox="[248,1362,194,1788]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1436,193,1790]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 97 – 103. Stigmella confertae Diškus &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 97, 99, habitat, páramo, 10 km W of Papallacta, Napo Province, Ecuador, the equatorial Andes, elevation 3700 – 3800 m; 98, host-plant Baccharis conferta Kunth; 100 – 102, leafmines; 103, forewing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/261805/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="125">
Figs 
<number id="3DD5D94CFFE1A132D5EC46D2AA29F875" box="[698,772,1970,1994]" pageId="24" pageNumber="125" value="97.99">97, 99</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30798E0FFE1A132D79146B6AD2FF851" box="[199,1026,2006,2031]" pageId="24" pageNumber="125" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA2CB6BFFE1A132D79146B6AD2FF851" blockId="24.[151,1436,1934,2031]" box="[199,1026,2006,2031]" pageId="24" pageNumber="125">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFE1A132D79146B6A863F850" bold="true" box="[199,334,2006,2031]" pageId="24" pageNumber="125">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after the host-plant 
<emphasis id="B9691779FFE1A132D47246B6AD2FF851" box="[804,1026,2006,2031]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="125">
<taxonomicName id="4C1DB0E8FFE1A132D47246B6AAD3F851" box="[804,1022,2006,2031]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Baccharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="24" pageNumber="125" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="conferta">Baccharis conferta</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30798E0FFE0A133D79141F7A83DFEA2" pageId="25" pageNumber="126" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA2CB6BFFE0A133D79141F7A83DFEA2" blockId="25.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFE0A133D79141F7A819FF0F" bold="true" box="[199,308,151,176]" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">Remarks</emphasis>
. This distinctive high altitude new species, associated with 
<taxonomicName id="4C1DB0E8FFE0A133D4BB41F7ADEBFF0F" box="[1005,1222,151,176]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Baccharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="conferta">
<emphasis id="B9691779FFE0A133D4BB41F7ADEBFF0F" box="[1005,1222,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">Baccharis conferta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a host-plant, is described from the genitalia slides dissected from adults still enclosed within the pupa shell. It seems, that this species is difficult to rear indoors (mortality rate is about 
<number id="3DD5D94CFFE0A133D41B41BFAABAFF47" box="[845,919,223,248]" pageId="25" pageNumber="126" value="92.5" valueMax="95.0" valueMin="90.0">90–95</number>
%; the causes of the high mortality remains unknown).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
